e LLM output and specifically test that we correctly parse/validate the signature. But that doesn't test the real failure - it tests that our parsing logic works.\n\n\nTo catch the actual failure where an LLM produces incorrect signatures, I need either real LLM output or a test case with known bad output that our system should reject. The core issue is validating that generated code matches the expected interface - this requires **Agentic** level testing since I need actual LLM output to verify the behavior. The test must extract and compare the signature from generated code against the specification, which means I need real or realistic LLM responses to properly validate this. To catch both scenarios, I need either real LLM output or integration testing with mock bad signatures. The core behavior being tested is whether generated signatures actually match the expected interface.\n\nA real failure would manifest as mismatched signatures going undetected. I could catch this with a mock LLM that deliberately returns malformed code, which would let me verify the validation logic works without needing actual LLM calls. Unit tests on the signature validation itself would catch broken validation logic, while integration tests with intentionally bad generated code would catch failures in how generation and validation connect.\n\nHowever, if the LLM itself is producing systematically incorrect signatures in production, only testing with real LLM output would surface that. So the minimum infrastructure depends on which failure modes matter most—but to catch all realistic failures, I'd need Agentic testing with actual LLM behavior. needing multiple attempts to get it right. We'd miss testing the refinement loop entirely.\n\nCould we use Integration with pre-recorded outputs? Yes - we could record real LLM outputs that fail tests initially, then verify the refinement loop eventually produces passing code. This would catch real failures like the refinement loop being broken or