ting signatures from known code samples and verifying the comparison logic works correctly, rather than requiring a real LLM call. - Testing the full integration (Integration)\n\nThe question is whether these tests would catch the actual failure of \"LLM generated unexpected signature\". If the LLM produces something like `def my_func(*args: Unknown, **kwargs: Unknown) -> Unknown:` when we expect `def my_func(x: int, y: str) -> bool:`, a mocked LLM in an Integration test might not surface this. Only testing with a real LLM would expose such signature mismatches. This means **Agentic** testing is needed for behavior 1.\n\nFor behavior 3, I can verify that failure messages get included in refinement prompts at the Integration level by mocking the test runner to return failures, then checking that subsequent LLM calls contain those error messages. This would catch the real bug where failure messages aren't being passed along. So **Integration** is appropriate here.\n\nBehavior 4 involves the service stopping after 3 failed attempts. The real failure would be if we keep retrying indefinitely instead of halting. I need to mock the LLM to always return failing code, then verify the service stops at exactly 3 attempts and that the result tracks all 3 attempts. This is testable at **Integration** level since I'm not relying on real LLM behavior, just the retry logic itself.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13359,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13359},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6f1b3141-a23d-4d9e-bbd5-ea445cbc7096","uuid":"337ca1c3-007c-478b-86f5-a8b5e0395e45"}
