{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01NHUf5YNQuB1f1ZHfAN62fo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01En53oYX5RYnXhcQbFKWiep","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The real failure is: an LLM generates code with a signature that doesn't match the expected interface (e.g., extra parameters, wrong types, missing return annotation), and the system doesn't detect it. To catch this, we must test with real LLM output, because the LLM might generate unexpected signature patterns (type hints as 'Any', extra *args/**kwargs, different parameter names) that a mock wouldn't produce. An Integration-level test with a mocked LLM would pass but miss real LLM signature failures. We need to call the real LLM (or use real recorded outputs that show signature mismatches) to have confidence the validation logic works against actual LLM behavior.","test_description":"Call the real LLM with a natural language description of a function interface (e.g., 'function that takes two integers and returns a boolean'). Parse the generated code, extract its signature (parameter names, types, return type), and verify it matches the specified interface. Repeat with several function descriptions. If parsing fails or signature mismatch isn't detected, the test fails.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated implementation passes all provided test cases on the first or a subsequent attempt.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The real failure is: the LLM generates code that fails tests, refinement is attempted, but the final code still doesn't pass (either because refinement 