":"Mock the LLM to return code that will fail the test suite on first attempt. Mock the test runner to report specific failure messages (e.g., 'AssertionError: expected output X, got Y'). Trigger code generation and watch it attempt refinement. Capture the second LLM call's prompt argument. Verify that the second prompt includes the captured failure messages in a clear format (e.g., 'Test failures: ...'). Assert that removing failure messages from the prompt-building logic causes this test to fail.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is: the iteration limit is broken (stops at 2, or doesn't stop at 3, or loops infinitely). This depends only on the loop counter logic and error-response structure, neither of which depends on LLM output quality. We can mock the LLM to always return code that fails tests, then verify the system makes exactly 3 calls and stops. The error response structure can be validated against the mock results. An Integration test with a failing mock fully covers this — no real LLM non-determinism affects the stopping logic.","test_description":"Mock the LLM to always return code that fails the test suite (deterministically). Trigger code generation and refinement. Verify that the LLM is called exactly 3 times, no more. Verify that after the 3rd failed attempt, the service returns a structured error response that includes: (a) all 3 generated code attempts, (b) test results for each attempt, (c) an error message indicating max attempts reached. Verify that a 4th LLM call is never made.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full loop — generate, test, refine, test again — produces a working implementation for a function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This is an end-to-end behavior that depends entirely on real LLM output and real LLM improvement over iterations. The real failure is: the system can't produce working code even when the LLM is given failure messages, because iteration doesn't actually help the real LLM improve (or the loop is broken). An Integration-level test with a mock LLM returning 'fail-then-pass' patterns would pass but miss the real failure where the real LLM either doesn't improve with feedback or generates code that's consistently incorrect. The behavior explicitly tests iterative improvement, which is inherently about real LLM non-determinism and learning. Outcomes vary across runs (different LLM calls produce different code), and only real LLM execution reveals whether the loop actually helps.","test_description":"Select a function specification that is known to be difficult (e.g., a complex algorithm or edge-case-heavy logic that single-shot generation typically fails on). Call the real LLM to generate an initial implementation. Run the code against the test suite. If it fails, extract the failure messages and request refinement. Repeat until tests pass or max attempts reached. Verify that the final code passes all tests. Document the attempt count. Repeat this test 5+ times to account for LLM non-determinism. Ensure that at least 80% of runs succeed (code passes tests at attempt ≤ 3).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13359,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13359},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},